{"annotations": [{"id": ["NCBIGene:6646"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "STAT family", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.975510835647583, "span": {"begin": 4, "end": 15}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3716"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "JAK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9949340224266052, "span": {"begin": 156, "end": 159}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6646"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "STAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9935952425003052, "span": {"begin": 160, "end": 164}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6646"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "STAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9857007265090942, "span": {"begin": 205, "end": 209}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014443"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tyrosine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9600217938423157, "span": {"begin": 286, "end": 294}}, {"id": ["mesh:C008887"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "phospho", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.7648115754127502, "span": {"begin": 328, "end": 335}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6776"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "STAT5", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9652767181396484, "span": {"begin": 406, "end": 411}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6776"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "STAT5", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9864223599433899, "span": {"begin": 468, "end": 473}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mammary epithelial cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9167003631591797, "span": {"begin": 514, "end": 538}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9940"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "sheep", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8849356770515442, "span": {"begin": 542, "end": 547}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5617"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "prolactin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9668526649475098, "span": {"begin": 636, "end": 645}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6776", "6777"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "STAT5 proteins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9895342588424683, "span": {"begin": 690, "end": 704}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cytoplasm", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.4968614876270294, "span": {"begin": 754, "end": 763}}], "text": "The STAT family of proteins regulate gene transcription upon activation. The proteins rely on cytokine signaling and a number of growth factors through the JAK/STAT&nbsp; pathway (Kisseleva, et al. 2002). STAT activation is regulated by phosphorylation of protein monomers at conserved tyrosine residues, followed by binding to phospho-peptide pockets and subsequent dimerization (Gianti and Zauhar 2015). STAT5 has been implicated in cell growth and differentiation. STAT5 was originally purified and cloned from mammary epithelial cells in sheep and identified as a signal transducer that confers the specific biological responses of prolactin (Wakao, et al. 1992, Xu, et al. 1996).Thus, STAT5 proteins function as signal transduction molecules in the cytoplasm and as transcription factors upon translocation to the nucleus.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:46:40 +0000 2026"}